</description><pubDate>Tue, 24 Jan 2017 17:59:49 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">http://www.muddlingthru.ca:80/find-an-azure-function-s-repository-to-clone-it-locally</guid></item><item><title>C# Nullable Type</title><link>http://www.muddlingthru.ca:80/c-nullable-type</link><description>&lt;p&gt;How does it work?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;it is a struct that wraps a struct&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;if the underlying struct has a value, then
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;HasValue&lt;/code&gt; is true and &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;Value&lt;/code&gt; returns the value.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;if the underlying struct lacks a value, then 
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;HasValue&lt;/code&gt; is false and &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;Value&lt;/code&gt; throws an &lt;code&gt;InvalidOperationException&lt;/code&gt;. &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;GetValueOrDefault()&lt;/code&gt; always returns the inner struct's default value.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When is it useful?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It is useful when we do NOT want to assume that the user (or client application, or data source...) provided the default value, when in fact the user (or client app...) provided no value.&lt;/p&gt;

